07158nam a22010095i 9783110711592DE-B159720220424125308.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220424t20212021gw     fo  d z      eng d  a2021940278  a97831107115927 a10.1515/97831107115922doi  a(DE-B1597)562971  a(OCoLC)1266229178  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE00aP167b.I58 2021. 4aP167b.I68 2021 7aLAN0060002bisacsh04a42522300aInterfaces in Functional Discourse Grammar :bTheory and Applications /ced. by Daniel García Velasco, Lucía Contreras-García. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter Mouton, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (XI, 446 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aTrends in Linguistics. Studies and Monographs [TiLSM] ,x1861-4302 ;v35400tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAbbreviations -- tFunctional Discourse Grammar: Blueprint and interfaces -- tInterfaces, mismatches, and the architecture of Functional Discourse Grammar -- tGrammar in 5D: The interface design of a mismatching grammar -- tPhonology and phonetics in Functional Discourse Grammar: Interfaces, mismatches, and the direction of processing -- tNoun incorporation in Functional Discourse Grammar -- tA Functional Discourse Grammar typology of reflexives, with some notes on reciprocals -- tSerial verb constructions, interface mismatches and Functional Discourse Grammar -- tA Functional Discourse Grammar account of voice in Plains Algonquian Languages -- tThe English ‘Time-measurement construction’ as a case of gradience: A Functional Discourse Grammar approach -- tInter-level mismatches in English coordinated partitives -- tA Functional Discourse Grammar account of postnominal modification in English -- tMeaning-to-form mismatches in Functional Discourse Grammar and Systemic Functional Grammar: A case study of the English discourse connective however -- tSubject Index -- tName Index -- tLanguage Index0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn grammar design, a basic distinction is made between derivational and modular architectures. This raises the question of which organization of grammar can deal with linguistic phenomena more appropriately. The studies contained in the present volume explore the interface relations between different levels of linguistic representation in Functional Discourse Grammar as presented in Hengeveld and Mackenzie (2008) and Keizer (2015). This theory analyses linguistic expressions at four linguistic levels: interpersonal, representational, morphosyntactic and phonological. The articles address issues such as the possible correspondences and mismatches between those levels as well as the conditions which constrain the combinations of levels in well-formed expressions. Additionally, the theory is tested by examining various grammatical phenomena with a focus both on the English language and on typological adequacy: anaphora, raising, phonological reduction, noun incorporation, reflexives and reciprocals, serial verbs, the passive voice, time measurement constructions, coordination, nominal modification, and connectives. Overall, the volume provides both theoretical and descriptive insights which are of relevance to linguistics in general.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aFunctional discourse grammar. 4aGrammatik. 4aTheoretische Linguistik. 4aTypologie. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Grammar & Punctuation.2bisacsh  aFunctional Discourse Grammar, Linguistic Interfaces.  aLinguistic Typology.  aThe Architecture of Grammar.1 aContreras-García, Lucía, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aContreras-García, Lucía, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aEsteban, Avelino Corral, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.